04598nam a22005775i 9780520921023DE-B159720240306123113.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t19941994cau    fo  d z      eng d  a97805209210237 a10.1525/97805209210232doi  a(DE-B1597)648596  a(OCoLC)1419789939  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  acaucUS-CA 4aML60b.K37 1994 7aMUS0000002bisacsh04a7802201 aKerman, Joseph, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aWrite All These Down :bEssays on Music /cJoseph Kerman; ed. by Joseph Kerman. 1aBerkeley, CA : bUniversity of California Press, c[1994] 4cÂ©1994  a1 online resource (359 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tPreface -- tCRITICISM -- t1 A Profile for American Musicology -- t2 How We Got into Analysis, and How to Get Out -- t3 A Few Canonic Variations -- t4 Critics and the Classics -- tBYRD, TALLIS,ALFONSO FERRABOSCO -- t5 William Byrd and Elizabethan Catholicism -- t6 Byrd, Tallis, and the Art of Imitation -- t7 "Write All These Down": Notes on a Song by Byrd -- t8 The Missa Puer natus est by Thomas Tallis -- t9 An Italian Musician in Elizabethan England -- tBEETHOVEN -- t10 Tovey's Beethoven -- t11 An die ferne Geliebte -- t12 Taking the Fifth -- t13 Beethoven's Minority -- tOPERA AND CONCERTO -- t14 Translating The Magic Flute -- t15 Wagner: Thoughts in Season -- t16 Verdi's Use of Recurring Themes -- t17 Two Early Verdi Operas; Two Famous Terzetti -- t18 Reading Don Giovanni -- t19 Mozart's Piano Concertos and Their Audience -- t20 Tristan und Isolde: The Prelude and the Play -- tAcknowledgments -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIf one name stands out among musicologists writing today, that name is Joseph Kerman. Eminent, wide-ranging, and wonderfully readable, Kerman's writing on musicology, opera, Beethoven, and Elizabethan music has informed and inspired an extensive audience both in America and abroad.There is much to interest both the general reader and the musicologist in this collection of twenty essays. Included are several notable pleas addressed by Kerman to his professional colleagues in an effort to get them to adopt a more critical orientation for their work. Other essays range from a moving account of William Byrd as a spokesman for the beleaguered Elizabethan Catholic minority to a discerning analysis of Beethoven's well-known obsession with the key of C minor. The controversial tenets of Kerman's classic Opera as Drama (1956) are reaffirmed in essays on Don Giovanni, The Magic Flute, Tristan und Isolde, Ernani and I Lombardi.Kerman's legacy to a younger generation is here, too: in an exemplary writing style, he offers challenging models for a humane and historically informed music criticism. An added gem is the Preface, which provides an intellectual and anecdotal road map of the place of the essays in Kerman's academic and public expeditions.Joseph Kerman has been at the very center of musicology for almost four decades. This overview of his work will be warmly received and greatly valued.  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aMusicxHistory and criticism. 0aMusical criticism. 4aGeneral. 4aMusic. 7aMUSIC / General.2bisacsh1 aKerman, Joseph, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Package Archive Pre-2000z97831106353480 cprintz978052021377740uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/978052092102340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520921023423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520921023/original  a978-3-11-063534-8  University of California Press Package Archive Pre-2000b2000